uncle peevi&s;hly) I have no rea&s;on to
flatter my&s;elf that my di&s;order comes
within the efficacy of your no&s;t$um.
But, this patient you talk of, may not
be &s;o &s;ound at bottom as you ima|gine.&endq;
&startq;I can't po&s;&s;ibly be mi&s;taken:
(rejoined the philo&s;opher) for I have
had communication with her three
times&mdash;I always a&s;certain my cures in
that manner.&endq; At this remark, all the
ladies retired to another corner of the
room, and &s;ome of them began to &s;pit.&mdash;
As to my uncle, though he was ruffled at
fir&s;t by the doctor's &s;aying he was drop&s;i|cal,
he could not help &s;miling at this ri|diculous
confe&s;&s;ion, and, I &s;uppo&s;e, with
a view to puni&s;h this original, told him
there was a wart upon his no&s;e, that
looked a little &s;u&s;picious. &startq;I don't pre|tend
to be a judge of tho&s;e matters;
(&s;aid he) but I under&s;tand that warts
are often produced by the di&s;temper;
and that one upon your no&s;e &s;eems to
have taken po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the very key|&s;tone
of the bridge, which I hope is in
no danger of falling.&endq; L&mdash;n &s;eem|ed
a little confounded at this remark, and
a&s;&s;ured him it was nothing but a com|mon
<PB N="32" REF="45">
excre&s;cence of the cuticula, but that
the bones w$$e all &s;ound below; for the
truth of this a&s;&s;ertion he appealed to the
touch, de&s;iring he would feel the part.
My uncle &s;aid it was a matter of &s;uch de|licacy
to meddle with a gentleman's no&s;e,
that he declined the office&mdash;upon which,
the Doctor turning to me, intreated me
to do him that favour. I complied with
his reque&s;t, and handled it &s;o roughly,
that he &s;neezed, and the tears ran down
his cheeks, to the no &s;mall entertainment
of the company, and particularly of my
uncle, who bur&s;t out a-laughing for the
fir&s;t time &s;ince I have been with him;
and took notice, that the part &s;eemed to
be very tender. &startq;Sir, (cried the Doc|tor)
it is naturally a tender part; but
to remove all po&s;&s;ibility of doubt, I
will take off the wart this very
night.&endq;</P>
<P>So &s;aying, he bowed with great &s;olem|nity
all round, and retired to his own
lodgings, where he applied cau&s;tic to the
wart; but it &s;pread in &s;uch a manner as
to produce a con&s;iderable inflammation,
attended with an enormous &s;welling; &s;o
